prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Science Goal
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Continuum and line survey of MDCs in NGC6357.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Our goal is to resolve 5 km/s line width and to use the lines to study the kinematic outflow/infall of the cores. Choosing O.4 km/s of spectral resolution is perfect for a good profile sampling. In parallel, two basebands of 1875 MHz each are dedicated to the continnum imaging.

The size of our objects comes from the Herschel data: the mean size is 0.14+-0.042 pc (16 +- 4.94 arcsec). We want to resolve the cores into fragments (corresponding to single star cocoons) of typical size of 1000 UA corresponding to 0.6 arcsec at the distance of NGC 6357 (1.75 kpc). We then ask for a spatial resolution of 0.6 arcsec. For a single pointing the OT gives us with a maximum recoverable scale of 29.6 arcsec and a FOV of 67 arcsec which are larger enough respectively to our object's initial size.

First we used our Herschel data to determine the deconvolved size of MDCs as well as, thanks to the SED fitted curve, we estimated their ALMA 3mm continuum flux. For lines we based our sensitivity estimation on MALT90 observations. We extracted spectral line information (velocity, FWHM and peak intensity) for 17 sources of our sample which are covered by MALT90 (for MALT90 the beam is 38 arcsec and the spectral resolution is 0.11 km/s).
We based our ALMA time estimation on the H13CO+ (in ALMA band 3) as we are mainly interested by this optically thin kinematic tracer of the cores. We determine from MALT90 that for this line the typical line width is 5 km/s and peak intenstiy is 0.3 K. As we want a 0.6 arcsec resolution and a velocity resolution of 0.4 km/s for ALMA we obtain a typical line flux of 0.15 Jy per channel. We then adopt a 10 mJy sensitivity (10 sigma sensitivity).
In the ALMA sensitivity calculator we then enter 86.6 GHz, Bandwith 0.4 km/s, 10 mjy of sensitivity, resolution 0.6 arcsec. This gives us 5.86 min as integration time for one source. We also check from the OST tool (adopting the "modeled protostellar cluster" model) that the UV coverage obtained in this integration time allow us to reconstruct a good map of the targets.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The formation of massive stars (M>8 Msun) is still under of debate. To constrain the different high-mass star-forming models proposed it is important to search for and characterize the IR-quiet massive dense cores (MDCs), i.e. MDCs with no sign of ongoing star-formation, that are expected to be the progenitors of massive stars.In our Herschel study of the star-forming complex NGC 6357 (d = 1.75 kpc) we have found 26 such IR-quiet MDCs, with size between 0.07 and 0.2 pc. We propose continuum and molecular-line observations with ALMA to characterise these cores, particularly their spatial structure in search for fragmentation at sub-arcsec resolution (~ 0.6 arcsec, i.e. ~ 1000 AU), their evolutionary status (via their kinematic structure as infall/outflow motions) and the identification of pre-stellar massive cores.
